(first drafts/ poetic free writing)

I. First Questions

The first time that I asked of you was late,
in 2025, some ten months gone.
Aside from you yourself, I had to wait
and turn to others after sending one

small message out to you: How are you?—there,
the first plain question put into the air.
Then Lisa got the second, clean and bare:
What happened to Patsy? Tell me what was there.

She gave me lies, obfuscation, and
the line that you had married some man. I
sat with it long. The surface would not stand.
The falsehood showed too quickly to the eye.

And once I saw that, other things began:
the first bad answer opening the span.

II. Her Nightmare

She has become impossibly at ease
in this, and thinks it funny, which is worse.
The trick is not the lie itself, but these
light little turns that make the false rehearse

Thirty-two years. All that I know is name:
Patsy Cline. The rest has fallen through.
Not even loss can perfectly proclaim
what was, when what remains is only you

reduced to syllables I cannot test
except by saying them and feeling space
begin to stir, then fail me like the rest,
leaving no world behind it but a trace.

Patsy Cline: no biography, no proof,
no history I can hold up to the light,
just that one name still standing like a roof
above a house withdrawn from human sight.

Thirty-two years, and this much still is mine:
the empty field made audible by Cline.

as social fact. Yet right upon the face
of it I saw the thing she could not risk,
the one event that would undo the case
and leave her manner suddenly not brisk:

that you and I might one day compare notes,
put fact by fact against her edited air,
and bring the hidden engine to our throats,
the thing she never wants brought open there.

That is her nightmare. So I cut her free.
The friendship ended where the truth might be.

III. Sunday Morn

And all of it runs backward to the start,
to Sunday morning, coffee, and return.
What stays is not the fiction, but the part
the body played, which language could not turn.

For when Lisa came back carrying the cup,
her face gave off two signals at one stroke:
how flushed she was, as something had come up,
and how pale too, as if beneath it broke

some other current. I remembered that.
Not what she later said, nor what she hid,
nor the convenient husband, nor the chat,
but that bare contradiction that she did

not mean to show: the color and the drain.
That was the first report that did remain.
